<div id="review_2747968395" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2747968395" />
    <a title="J. Stone" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7609802-j-stone"><img alt="J. Stone" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586006213p2/7609802.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2747968395?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J. Stone" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J. Stone" href="/user/show/7609802-j-stone">J. Stone</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2747968395" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1361425179415633679">Anne Rice continusouly stuns us with her prose, deeply developed characters and organic talent for setting, story and history. Cry To Heaven lived up to all my expectations, but Anne really never fails me as a reader. From the very first line of the book, we are pulled into a magnanimous story surrounding Italy&apos;s Eunuch tradition in the 18th century, and from there a rocket blasts back into time and introduces us to some of the most complicated and interesting characters I&apos;ve ever read in an Ann</span>
  <span id="freeText1361425179415633679" style="display:none">Anne Rice continusouly stuns us with her prose, deeply developed characters and organic talent for setting, story and history. Cry To Heaven lived up to all my expectations, but Anne really never fails me as a reader. From the very first line of the book, we are pulled into a magnanimous story surrounding Italy's Eunuch tradition in the 18th century, and from there a rocket blasts back into time and introduces us to some of the most complicated and interesting characters I've ever read in an Anne Rice novel. She is an addicting read, and rightfully so. She writes circles in her sleep around all of her colleagues. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1361425179415633679" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


